description: A suspicious process related to a likely malicious file was launched. Review any binaries involved as they might be related to malware.

description: A net process attempted to mount a One Drive share. This technique is used by adversaries in targeted attacks. If this is unexpected, review the process tree.

description: OverWatch identified malicious activity. Investigate the process tree.

name: Webshell

description: A process launched whose behavior is likely related to a potentially unwanted program (PUP). Review the file.
name: PUP

description: A process launched, and its behavior is likely related to adware. Review the process tree.

description: A process tree contains commands that some adversaries use for reconnaissance, but are also used by some system administrators. If this activity is unexpected, review the process tree.

name: MaliciousModule

description: A process engaged in network activity with a remote destination known for malicious activity. Investigate events around the remote connection.

description: The process behavior appears to be related to a Java-based remote administration tool (RAT). Review the process tree.

description: A file appears to be imitating a standard OS or otherwise benign filename and/or launched from an unusual location. This might be to masquerade malware. Review the file.

description: OverWatch identified malicious activity. Investigate the process tree.
name: OverWatchDetection

description: A process made a suspicious change to the registry that might indicate a malicious persistence mechanism. Investigate the registry key.
name: RegistryPersistEdit

description: The process shows signs of data being exfiltrated from your environment. If this is unexpected, review the process tree.
name: Exfiltration

description: A script launched from a location associated with a remote administration tool (RAT). RATs often blend in with other benign applications and might be used by adversaries to remotely control the host. Review the script.

description: A process launched that shares characteristics with a cryptocurrency miner. If this is unexpected, review the process tree.

description: An unusual process accessed lsass. This might indicate an attempt to dump credentials. Investigate the process tree.

description: A module was loaded from an unusual path or with an unusual file name. Review the DLLs loaded by the process.

description: PowerShell launched with a base64 encoded command line that appears to be a malicious payload. This might be related to a PowerShell exploit kit or dropper. Review the encoded script.
name: PShellBase64

description: A Java application launched from an unusual location. This might be a Java-based remote administration tool (RAT). Investigate the process tree.
name: JavaUnusualLoc

description: PowerShell loaded a script from a base64 encoded value stored in the host's registry hive. The base64 encoded value is likely a malicious payload. Investigate the registry key entry.
name: PShellBase64FromReg

description: PowerShell launched an unusual number of encoded commands, one after another. This is often a sign of a PowerShell based exploit kit. Investigate the process tree.
name: PShellMultiEncoded

description: Mshta launched an unusual PowerShell command. This might originate from a remote procedure call or a macro initiated by a malicious document. Decode the PowerShell command and investigate the mshta process source.
name: MshtaPShell

description: PowerShell launched as a service in an unusual way. An adversary might have scheduled malicious code to run. Investigate scheduled tasks on the host.
name: PShellService

description: A PowerShell script attempted to bypass Microsoft's AntiMalware Scan Interface (AMSI). PowerShell exploit kits often attempt to bypass AMSI to evade detection. Review the script.
name: PShellAmsi

description: A PowerShell script launched that shares characteristics with known PowerShell exploit kits. The script might connect to remote command and control. Decode and review the script.
name: PShellExploitKit2

description: A PowerShell process downloaded and launched a remote file. This is often the result of a malicious macro designed to drop a variety of second stage payloads. Review the command line.
name: PShellDownloadRun

description: A PowerShell script appears to be using obfuscation to evade detection. Obfuscated scripts are often associated with malicious activity. Review the script.
name: PShellObfuscated

description: A PowerShell process launched under an email app with an unusual command line. This might indicate a phishing attack. Investigate the process tree and determine the script execution source.
name: EmailToPShell

description: A script other than PowerShell unexpectedly launched a PowerShell process with suspicious command line arguments. This might indicate a malicious dropper. Investigate the process tree.
name: ScriptToPShell

description: A PowerShell script launched that shares characteristics with known PowerShell cryptomining software. The script might mine bitcoins and connect to remote command and control. Decode and review the script.
name: PShellCryptoMining

description: PowerShell unexpectedly wrote and ran an executable. PowerShell is often abused as a dropper for malicious payloads. Investigate the process tree.
name: PShellWroteAndRan

description: A process loaded a likely malicious DLL. This is indicative of activity to take advantage of the Windows DLL search order to gain persistence or elevated privileges on the system. Review the process tree.
name: GenericDllHijackingPersistence

description: A process encoded or otherwise obfuscated the contents of a file. Adversaries can obfuscate information to avoid detection. Review the process tree.
name: GenericObfuscatedFilesOrInfoDefenseEvasion

description: A process accessed data from the clipboard. Adversaries can abuse the Windows API to steal sensitive information residing on the clipboard. Review the process tree.
name: GenericClipboardDataCollection

description: A process loaded a likely malicious DLL. This is indicative of activity to take advantage of the Windows DLL search order to gain persistence or elevated privileges on the system. Review the process tree.
name: GenericDllHijackingPrivEsc

description: A process accessed data from the local file system. This might indicate an attempt to steal information. Review the accessed files and process tree.
name: GenericDataFromLocalSystemCollection

description: A process appears to be staging data. Adversaries can migrate data to a central location prior to exfiltration. Review the accessed files and process tree.
name: GenericDataStagedCollection

description: A process attempted to communicate using a standard application layer protocol, possibly to a command and control server. Adversaries can use this to blend in with normal network traffic and evade detection. Review the process tree.
name: GenericStandardAppLayerProtocolC2

description: A process attempted to establish an unusual connection over a commonly used port, possibly to a command and control server. Adversaries can use this to bypass firewalls and evade detection. Review the process tree.
name: GenericCommonlyUsedPortC2

description: A process attempted to communicate using a standard cryptographic protocol, possibly to a command and control server. Adversaries can use this to conceal traffic. Review the process tree.
name: GenericStandardCryptographicProtocolC2

description: A process appears to be gathering credentials that were stored in files. Adversaries can search the local file system to steal user account names and passwords. Review the accessed files and change your passwords if any credentials were stolen.
name: GenericCredentialsInFilesCredentialAccess

description: A process decoded or otherwise deobfuscated the contents of a file. Adversaries can use this to shape follow-on behavior. Review the process tree.
name: GenericDeobfuscateFilesOrInfoDefenseEvasion

description: A user executed an unusual file. Adversaries can lure users into executing malicious code using spearphishing and other trickery. Review the executable and process tree.
name: GenericUserExecution

description: An executable appears to have been manipulated to evade detection. Adversaries can abuse file names, paths, and headers to masquerade malware as a safe or legitimate file. Review the executable and process tree.
name: GenericMasqueradingDefenseEvasion

description: A process appears to be gathering private key information. Adversaries can use this for authentication or future collection efforts. Review the process tree.
name: GenericPrivateKeysCredentialAccess

description: A process compressed data from the local file system. Adversaries often compress data prior to transferring it across a network to increase portability. Review the process tree.
name: GenericDataCompressedExfiltration

description: A process encrypted data from the local file system. Adversaries often encrypt data during exfiltration to hide the information that is stolen and to evade detection. Review the process tree.
name: GenericDataEncryptedExfiltration

description: WMI Event Subscriptions were abused to persist suspicious code for execution. Adversaries can use this to maintain their foothold on a system. Review the process tree.
name: GenericWMIEventSubscriptionPersistence

description: A process wrote an executable file to a remote location. Adversaries can use this for lateral movement efforts. Review the process tree.
name: GenericRemoteFileCopyLateralMovement

description: A process is collecting user input. Adversaries can use this technique to steal sensitive information. Review the process tree.
name: GenericInputCaptureCollection

description: The BCDEdit tool was used to disable operating system recovery features. Adversaries may use this technique to prevent data restoration after a ransomware infection. Review the process tree.
name: BCDEditRecoveryDisable

description: Developer Options enabled in the Settings app. Trigger based on periodic scan and content observer on System Settings.
name: DeveloperOptionsEnabled

description: Privileged control (root access) that bypasses built-in security restrictions. Trigger based on a periodic scan and scan after boot, adb enabled or developer options enabled.
name: RootAccessDetected

description: Privileged control (root access) that bypasses built-in security restrictions. Trigger based on a periodic scan and scan after boot.
name: IOSSecurityCompromised

description: System partition is accessible to apps. Trigger based on a periodic scan and scan after boot.
name: FileSystemAttributesAltered

description: The Wi-Fi hotspot or cellular network attempted to decrypt and relay messages instead of establishing direct encrypted communications.

description: Lock Screen has not been set in the device. Trigger based on a periodic scan.
name: LockScreenNotSet

description: Apps are installed from outside the PlayStore. Trigger based on a System callback when apps are installed or updated.

description: SELinux module is disabled, the device is more vulnerable to apps violating Android's access control policy and to privilege escalation attacks. Trigger based on a periodic scan.
name: SELinuxDisabled

description: SafetyNet compatibility check failed, the device entered a tampered state where it is unsafe to run applications on. Trigger based on a periodic scan.
name: SafetyNetCompatibilityCheckFailed

description: Storage Encryption has been turned off. Trigger based on a periodic scan.
name: StorageNotEncrypted

description: System partition has been modified
name: SystemPartitionModified

description: Apps are allowed to be installed from outside the PlayStore. Trigger based on a periodic scan.
name: UnknownSourcesEnabled

description: BootLoader is in unlocked state. Trigger based on a periodic scan.
name: BootLoaderUnlocked

description: If corporate policy is to only have the app in the container but the user downloads a personal use copy of it. Trigger based on a System callback when apps are installed or updated.
name: DuplicateAppInstalledFromPlayStore

description: Google SafetyNet API found a harmful app installed on the device. Trigger based on periodic scan or System callback.
name: HarmfulAppFound

description: Debuggable flag is default false for non dev builds. Detection of flag to be true. Trigger based on periodic scan.
name: DebuggableFlagTurnedOn

description: User does not provide permission to Android sensor to verify device apps using Google SafetyNet API. Trigger based on periodic scan.
name: VerifyAppsDisabled

description: Google SafetyNet API found a harmful app installed on the device from the Play Store. Trigger based on periodic scan or System callback.
name: HarmfulAppInstalledFromPlayStore
